lsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356350,"age":105,"year":"1500","julianDay":2268924,"description":"The Ottoman Empire invades Austria.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret ferch Llewelyn was born in 1395, in Vienna, Austria. She married Gruffudd ap Jerwerth in Hungary. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1395–":"1395–Surnud","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1420–1455":"1420–1455","1425–1455":"1425–1455","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1395":"1395","Carrog, Corwen, Merioneth, Wales":"Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Vienna, , Wien, Austria":"Wien, Austria","Austria, Hungary